<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="voting" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Voting</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        This chapter introduces fundamental concepts of voting and democratic decision-making.
        We explore basic voting methods and their applications in various contexts.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-voting-basics">
    <title>Basic Voting Concepts</title>
    
    <p>
        In a democracy, voting is the primary mechanism by which citizens make collective decisions.
        This section introduces the fundamental concepts and terminology used in voting theory.
    </p>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-preference">
      <title>Preference</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>preference</term> is an ordering of candidates or alternatives from most preferred to least preferred.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-ballot">
      <title>Ballot</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>ballot</term> is a way of recording a voter's preference among the candidates or alternatives.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-voting-method">
      <title>Voting Method</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>voting method</term> (or voting system) is a procedure for determining the winner of an election based on the ballots cast.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </section>
  
  <section xml:id="sec-simple-voting">
    <title>Simple Voting Methods</title>
    
    <p>
        We begin with some of the most straightforward voting methods used in elections.
    </p>
    
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-plurality">
      <title>Plurality Method</title>
      
      <p>
          The plurality method is perhaps the most familiar voting method.
      </p>
      
      <definition xml:id="def-plurality">
        <title>Plurality Method</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In the <term>plurality method</term>, each voter votes for exactly one candidate, and the candidate with the most votes wins.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
    </subsection>
  </section>
</chapter>